
  <sn><md>## Calvin Cycle {.text-center}

The **Calvin Cycle**, also known as the **C₃ cycle** or **light-independent reactions**, is the biochemical pathway through which plants, algae, and some bacteria convert **carbon dioxide (CO₂)** into **glucose**. It takes place in the **stroma of chloroplasts** and uses the **ATP and NADPH** generated during the light reactions.

Although the Calvin Cycle does not directly require light, it depends on light-produced molecules (ATP &amp; NADPH), so it is `indirectly light-dependent`.


