<sn><md>### Overview of the Calvin Cycle{.text-center}

The Calvin Cycle consists of **three main stages**:

1. `Carbon Fixation`
2. `Reduction`
3. `Regeneration of RuBP`

The cycle must turn **three times** to fix **three molecules of CO₂**, generating `one molecule of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (G3P)`, the ++precursor for glucose++.

![diagram](https://www.sciencephoto.com/image/f0419794/800wm)</md></sn><sn><md>### Carbon Fixation

```
CO₂ + RuBP --(RuBisCO)--&gt; 3-PGA
```

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Step Details{.text-center}
* The enzyme **RuBisCO** (Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/oxygenase) captures **CO₂** from the environment.
* CO₂ combines with **RuBP** (Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate), a 5-carbon compound.
* RuBP + CO₂ → **unstable 6-carbon compound** → splits immediately into:

  * **Two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate (3-PGA)**
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Key Points{.text-center}
* RuBisCO is the **most abundant enzyme on Earth**.
* This is the “fixing” of inorganic carbon into an organic form.
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Reduction Phase{.text-center}

```
3-PGA + ATP + NADPH → G3P
```

During this phase, **ATP and NADPH** from light reactions are used to convert 3-PGA into a more `energy-rich molecule`.

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Steps{.text-center}
1. ATP phosphorylates 3-PGA → **1,3-bisphosphoglycerate**
2. NADPH reduces it → **Glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (G3P)**
:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Importance of G3P {.text-center}
* G3P is a **3-carbon sugar**.
* Two G3P molecules combine to form **glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆)**.
* Out of every 6 molecules of G3P produced, **only 1 exits the cycle** to make sugars; the rest regenerate RuBP.
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Regeneration of RuBP{.text-center}

To keep the cycle running, the CO₂ acceptor **RuBP** must be regenerated.

```
G3P → (1 exits for glucose)
Remaining G3P + ATP → RuBP (regenerated)
```

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Steps{.text-center}
* The remaining **5 molecules of G3P** (out of 6) are rearranged using **ATP** to regenerate **3 molecules of RuBP**.
* These RuBP molecules can again accept CO₂ and restart the cycle.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Energy Requirement{.text-center}
* This step also consumes ATP, emphasizing dependence on the light reaction products.
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Energy and Input–Output Summary

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Inputs:{.text-center}
* **3 CO₂**
* **9 ATP**
* **6 NADPH**
:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Outputs:{.text-center}
* **1 G3P (net)**
* **9 ADP + 8 Pi (return to light reactions)**
* **6 NADP⁺ (return to light reactions)**
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Overall Significance

* **Production of Glucose** : The main purpose is to create **G3P**, which is used to synthesize-Glucose,Sucrose,Starch,Cellulose
* **Carbon Fixation** :  The Calvin Cycle helps remove CO₂ from the atmosphere, influencing global carbon balance.
* **Universal Pathway in C₃ Plants** :  The cycle is used by all plants using C₃ photosynthesis (most plants on Earth).
</md></sn><sn><md>### Simplified Diagram

